Moving towards Gender Equality in Surfing
Growing up in a beach town you tend to be drawn towards the ocean and surfing. That's just what happens and what makes sense. Personally, I have a dad who is a big character in the surf community near me. So for me of course I was going to surf but I was also going to fit into the surf community with no effort. I did not have to prove anything. For me, it was a birthright. However, it doesn't work out like that for all people who end up surfing especially if you are a female. Back in the day, females had to fight for respect in the water.  This gender difference was apparent. However, today, surfing is making moves to include the female population. Even though there is movement in the right direction for gender equality, there are still differences that exist.
Surfing throughout the years has always been more of a masculine sport and the guys have always been the people to do it. Back when my dad was starting to surf in the late 80s there were very few females in the water. There would be about ten males per every one female out in the water. Even when females would paddle out they would never get the best waves. They were seen by other surfers as a joke and did not get any respect for the sport. This was not only obvious to the surfers but was also evident when surf videos were released. Lost, a board company, put out many videos such as Lost Across America. These videos did not show females surfing. Girls were shown in bikinis on the beach. There wasn’t a market for women surfers. Even in the professional surfing world, women professional surfers were not recognized. There was not a large crowd when a woman was competing and when there was publicity, it was more about how they look then what they could do in the water. Then came Lisa Anderson. Although she did not wear a bikini in the water, she was still pretty and femanine. Interviewing my dad, he believes that if Lisa Anderson was not pretty, she would not have made such an impact on surfing culture. Her parents did not support her surfing either. She ended up running away. One would have to think was this because she was a girl in a male sport? Would she have her parents' support if she were a boy? She was an aggressive surfer who started to get attention around 1997 and was bringing female surfing to life. Lisa Anderson still looked like a girl and did not change her appearance for surfing. She was not trying to fit into a man’s sport but was trying to be a woman in the sport of surfing. Even though Lisa Anderson started to get attention and could surf, she still carried the stereotype, she is “good for a girl”. She was not looked at to be on the same level as the guys and in all honesty she was not nearly as good of the male professionals at the time. During the early 90’s, there was even a time that women’s surfing was cancelled but the men's competition and the bikini contest still happened (Girls Can’t Surf, 2020). I would argue this would not happen today.
My brother and I grew up in a different era but in the same surf culture. When we began surfing, we were young and there were not a lot of surfer girls. However, by the time I turned 13, this had changed. There were girls and boys in the water and we surfed together without any issues or ill feelings. We did not tell the girls they were bad and did not belong here. On the contrary, we welcomed them and enjoyed having them out in the water. We were raised with girl surfers in the water. They are a part of the surfing community. They have been backed by sponsorships and compete at high levels. The girls are just as aggressive as the boys. Locally, there is not much difference between a boy and girl surfer. It is evident now how surfing is more accepting to females. 
Gender inequality is evident in all cultures. In West and Zimmerman’s article, Do Gender, men and women have differences, “differences seemingly supported by the division of labor into women’s and men’s work...men are men and women are women” (p. 128). There are stereotypes for women and men in our society.  Women are not supposed to compete in a “men’s sport”.  Men are strong while women do not have the same ability.   As we talk in class about the ranks of the people you have, the white male leads everything and that is like being in first place. Then you have black males and white women. Then the last is black women. This is kind of the list for everything and just how people look at other people. Although gender differences do exist, the rank between men and women is starting to shrink as well as the gender roles are changing everyday in the surf world.  In the surfing world, men were dominant.  Women were not welcomed and treated negatively.  
In a 2017 op-ed for The Guardian, the seven-time world champion Layne Beachley described how from her first days of learning to surf to her years on the pro circuit in the 1990s, she and other women were heavily harassed, discriminated against, and paid a fraction of what their men competitors earned. “I was teased, cut off, told to get out of the water because I was a girl, advised that girls don’t surf, and to go mind the towel on the beach,” Beachley wrote of her early years surfing. “These encounters taught me to stand up and fight for what I believed in. (Baird, 2019)


Many times when a sport has a women’s division, they are thought of outside of their gender roles. “Men positioned athletic women as dangerous and masculines lesbians” (Essell, p.115).  This is a common thread when men look at women athletes. Essell discusses in Barbie Dolls that the Rugby players felt they needed to show their femininity since the rules of the game were the same for both male and females and the sport is tough. “Rugby is unique among women’s sports in having the same rules and  equipment as  the  men’s  game.  The  sport  offered  identity  resources  for  the  women,  as athletes, because of its hypermasculine structure and style of play” (p. 112). Surfing also follows the same rules no matter what gender you are.  When women first started to surf, they did not show their femininity but focused on being tough and masculine to fit into the surfing world. The men surfers did not accept women surfers and made it clear in interviews and out in the water (Girls Can’t Surf, 2020). Lisa Anderson started to change women’s surfing.  She showed that beautiful women can be surfers. She did not wear a bikini but still showed her beauty.  Now there are a lot of female professional surfers that do not have that hypermasculine side to them. They dress like women and act like women. They are aggressive in the water. That may be compared to being masculine but they are not. However, the surfing world started to use beauty as an identity for women.  The surf culture did not think women had a place in surfing and should look attractive.  Magazines took pictures of women’s butts for ad campaigns not there surfing.  Rebecca Woods' sponsor even dropped her because she did not fit the profile. “In a 2016 piece on Australia’s ABC, the former pro surfer Rebecca Woods detailed how she was dropped by her sponsor Billabong because, she said, they favored surfers who wore bikinis and looked like models” (Baird, 2019). As a result, the gender in-equality continued by using women who “looked like models” instead of women who surfed. Male surfers made comments like about the women surfers never being as good as men and needing to look like women. (Girls Can’t Surf, 2020)	
Surfing is making efforts in gender equality. Locally and in the professional world. In 2019, the World Surf League (WSL) established equal prize money for men and women surfers.  The greatest surfer of all time, Kelly Slater supported the movement for women by saying, “The women on the tour deserve this change. I'm so proud that surfing is choosing to lead sports in equality and fairness. The female WSL athletes are equally committed to their craft as the male athletes and should be paid the same” (WSL, 2018). Slater is an icon to surfing and his support shows surfers the respect women are getting.  WSL also made more changes than just the prize money. CEO Sophie Goldschmidt explained, “This is the latest in a series of actions the League has undertaken to showcase our female athletes, from competing on the same quality waves as the men, to better locations, and increased investment and support” (WSL, 2018).  The organization has moved women’s events to combine with the men or to better surf spots. The sport has begun to show women as athletes not supermodels. Sponsors and magazines are showing women surfing and not focusing on what they are wearing. They are earning respect for the sport and women’s ability. However, there are still some differences.  Women are still not on the same level as the males when competing. You can really see it through the highschool surf team. National Scholastic Surfing Association (NSSA) does not allow girls to have the same number of surfers. A NSSA high school surf team consists of two female surfers, 6 male surfers and one long board surfer who can be male or female.  Even if you have females that are better than the males and are willing to surf on the men’s team, NSSA high school national competition will not allow for this change. They are concerned that boys will want to join the girls' event. This shows that there is still room to grow where gender is concerned. The skill level between males and females are different and as a result, there is still a gender separation. This has hurt my high school surf team. When I joined the surf team 5 years ago, the girls' competition was about standing up on a board. The girls were not good surfers. My Sophomore year, a freshman girl joined the team and she was a decent surfer. An even better surfer joined the surf team my junior year. By my senior year, we had too many girls who could surf and the surfer who competed my sophomore and junior year, who placed each year, had to sit out of the state competition due to the talent of the girls on our team. This is even more challenging this year. There are 4 girls who could compete but only 2 are permitted. Throughout this time, in 5 years, I have seen the change and respect for the girl surfers. Truly we were trying to get them to surf with the boys due to the talent they have. I witnessed a change at the NSSA competition. Girls are getting better and gaining respect. The girls are not just able to stand up, they are good surfers. One can see the respect and how surfing has grown on females through the talent and how much better the females are at surfing then the females that surfed a while ago. 	
The talent level has also grown not just on a small scale of a highschool surf team but also at the professional level. Women surfers are getting better and better. The boys have been throwing airs in contests for years and it is one of the most entertaining things about surfing. Carissa Moore landed the first air in female pro surfing 
April 9, 2021. This was being talked about in the surfing world and was a great accomplishment. This shows a step and improvement in women's surfing. The male surfers also praised her when she did this. They did not mock her accomplishment or make fun of her like Layne Beachley experienced in 1990 instead they congratulated her. Women surfers have been publicly recognized by their male peers.  In John John Florence’s instagram, he congratulates Carissa on winning the world tour.  He even posts her wave during the competition. This shows that women are also getting more respect from their male peers at the highest level of surfing.      
The difference in men and women pro surfing is the judging of the waves and the scores that the women get compared to the men in competitions. The women scoring criteria is easier than the men. A perfect example is going back to Carrissa Moore and landing an air reverse. She got a 9.9 but if a male surfer were to do that in a contest it would not be looked at as special.  However, if a guy did the air Carissa did he wouldn’t get any praise. Actually, he would not get any recognition. I do believe we will see this change as more female surfers start to do more radical moves in the water. For now, this difference continues to separate the genders and provide inequality. As the girls get better, so do the boys so the gap in ability continues to exist and expand. 
WIth the WSL supporting women surfers and making a stance financially for equality, the gender inequality gap should shrink. This shows that the highest level of competition for surfers believes that female surfing is important. There has also been a change for surf clinics for girls.  The WSL has added clinics to the tour for girl surfers and is going to clear the beach for these clinics. This shows progress from the late 80’s early 90’s when women were treated poorly in the water and not recognized for their surfing ability.  Surfers are more respectful now and more welcoming. It will be nice to see the movement in the future. Unfortunately, the gap still exists since there are more male than female competition.
As stated throughout this paper, the gender difference in surfing is moving in the right direction. There are more female surfers at the local level, more opportunities with female clinics for young surfers and equal pay for those that surf professionally.  The male counterparts are recognizing female surfers as talented.  They are congratulating them and supporting them instead of telling them to get out of the water. When professionals make change, so do the more local communities. Female surfers are continuing to be more and more accepted in the surf culture. Although there is still work to do in the surfing world between the male and female population, surfing is moving to close the gender inequality gap.

In the essay, “Microfoundations,” the writer points out that ritual burial began happening some point after the 50,000-45,000 years ago mark as evidenced by the Sungir site in Russia that dates a ritual burial that occurred 28,000 years ago for two young people and a 60-year-old male. The significance of this is the evidence of large groups working together for the complex ornamentation of the bodies, each with 3,000 ivory beads that appeared to have taken over an hour to make one single bead, and large mammoth tusks that were boiled to be straightened out on either side of all the bodies. The complex ornamentation and ritual burial then also point to the concept of religion at this time, which is something is not evidenced before the 50,000-year mark for early humans. This essay points to language perhaps being the catalyst for Humans creating the first early animist religions. As in both essays they cite religion as a type of refuge for social beings and in, “The Neurology of Religion,” it is seen that religion is responsible for the organizing of rituals, burials in the case of the last essay, within a community. Which to carry out such complicated, coordinated efforts, it is likely that language would have had to come first to create a religion to become a collective for either tribes or groups of early Humans to rally behind so as to become a part of it. 
Prior to 50,000 years ago humans did not have a capacity for complex speech that modern humans had that kept them in the same playing field as Neanderthals and other Hominids. But when the capacity was gained for complex speech, a rise in early Humans’ abilities to form animist religions sparked the beginning of the complex collective consciousnesses that would eventually make up modern human civilization and put Humans ahead of other Hominids.

The Sociological Concept of “The Stage” and How it is used to Demonstrate The Presentation of Self

Why do we act the way we do in social situations and how can the presentation of self be illustrated? “The Stage'' is an analogy presented by the Sociologist Erving Goffman, as a means to demonstrate the presentation of self. Life is just one big series of performances. Through this concept, the presentation of self becomes as simplistic as understanding the different components of theatre. In essence, the way any one person acts is based on what they believe their audience wants to see from them. It is essential for everyone to keep their “character” intact through each and every performance, and for them to assist others in their performances. For these reasons, “The Stage” is a very straightforward way to illustrate the presentation of self. We act the way we do because we are the performers on stage, and we must do what we believe the audience wants us to do given our character and the props available to us. Understanding why we do what we do is the first step in improving the way social interactions are carried out, and result in the formation of new interpersonal relationships. Through this concept we can gain understanding in how identity is self made and interaction based. 
The goal of the performer is to please their audience and stay in character while on stage. 
Whether it is genuine or not, it is the performers duty to give their audience a specific impression. In my case, I strive to give others the impression that I am a caring person who can and will be there for almost anyone. Although this is a pretty conscious effort that I make through social interactions, I feel that it is a facet of my true self. I genuinely care for others and want to give anyone a shoulder to lean on, just as I would hope others would do for me. However, for some people keeping up their character involves less than authentic interactions. There are times when it can be apparent to others that their reasoning is not genuine. For myself and many others, detecting such actions has become almost second nature- although some people are better at hiding their true intentions than others. This skill is very useful when distinguishing genuine actions from ingenuine actions, thus preventing negative outcomes from social interactions. It is especially useful when making interpersonal and/or romantic relationships. 
Many social interactions are ridden with embarrassment, misunderstanding, and unnecessary aggressions because we do not understand why we ourselves and others do and say what they do. So, if this inability to understand other reasoning for their actions is eliminated from the equation, we are left with viable social interactions that result in the understanding of one another and the formation of relationships. For example, embarrassment occurs when someone strays from the contents of their “character”. According to Goffman it is our duty to assist others in keeping their character intact, and that embarrassment feels awkward for all involved. Knowing why embarrassment occurs will allow us to assist others and ourselves with staying in character, and commending the emergence of our true selves when someone becomes embarrassed in social interactions. Because acting on the stage is an effort which is made through any and every social interaction, it can become tiring. Although it can and is an unnoticed human practice by many, it still requires mental effort, and therefore it will be mentally tiring. The solution to this is as simple as assisting and comforting others while socially interacting. By helping others avoid embarrassment or misunderstandings, you help yourself avoid such occurrences too. I myself make efforts to comfort others when they feel embarrassed, or are involved in some sort of misunderstanding. Even if I do not consider myself a friend of that person, I believe that it is possible to relate myself to almost anyone, and find the compassion to help them in a time of need. How can I better understand this person's actions? How can I put myself in their shoes? By asking these questions and interacting we can better understand others' reasoning behind their actions which leads to less embarrassment and misunderstandings. According to Goffman, it is our duty to assist others in their performances, and it is important that all performers are able to recognize the types of roles that each performer is trying to achieve.
Identity is self made and interaction based. According to Goffman, it is the coalition of all performances made by the performer, even performances that stray from their character. It is proven that the way people act  “front stage” or present in a collectively produced social situation, contrats from the way they act “backstage” or not present in a collectively produced social situation. Identity is also the outcome of the props a performer has available to them, or the circumstances that they perform under. For example, if someone’s character consists of being generous with all they have, and being a supporter and a provider for others, but they’re financials are lacking, they may not be able to perform as consistently with their character as they or others believe they should.  It is also heavily influenced by societal expectations and the collective consciousness. What does society expect from someone who plays their role? What are more specific expectations for their character? These expectations are derived from the collective consciousness. An example of this is the role of the Mother. It is widely thought that Mothers are the caretakers and the nurturers. Society expects Mothers to play this role at all times. Although a Mothers character involves much more specific qualities than these qualities alone, straying from this role is seen as immoral. Identity is the formulation of one's actions when performing and the expectations placed upon them which they are expected to adhere to when performing. 
In my opinion, “The Stage '' is the best way to illustrate the presentation of self. This analogy is a good means to visualize the roles we take on in various social situations. There have been multiple occasions where I have questioned my own, and others actions in a specific situation, and this concept has allowed me to gain understanding of these actions. For example, I attended a concert recently and when it came to an end my boyfriend and I walked outside to wait for our ride. I walked over to the band’s bus to see them while my boyfriend looked for our ride. As soon as I left his presence an intoxicated man with a bottle of liquor in hand approached me in a way that made me very uncomfortable. He attempted to convince me to come with him and made comments about my appearance. He did not seem to notice my discomfort through the interaction. Instead of doing what I should have done, I froze. I didn’t become combative when he made inappropriate comments, I simply tried to end the conversation and walk away but the man blocked me from leaving. I eventually managed to get away, but I felt as though I hadn’t acted in the way I should have. Normally, I would have tried to be very stern and get away quickly from the interaction, but at times when I am on my own- I do not have the will to carry myself out of such dangerous situations. I felt a sort of embarrassment knowing that I should have acted differently, and that the situation could have become much worse. A sense of loneliness washed over me as I fled the situation because I realized that no one had come to assist me. By using the concept of “The Stage”, I can form an understanding of why I felt the way I did when straying from my self made character. I believe that it is because my character resides in social interactions that I am unable to defend myself against such interactions when I am on my own. 
In conclusion, “The Stage” is the most fitting concept that can be used to demonstrate the presentation of self. It is a means to simplify and illustrate the presentation of self using the different roles involved in theatre. This concept provides simplistic visuals of the various roles played in social situations. “The Stage '' is an interaction based concept used to illustrate the presentation of self.  According to the concept, identity is the coalition of performances the performer carries out through social situations. It is collectively produced by everyone involved in helping it emerge and grow. The goal of the performer is to keep their character intact by acting in a way that pleases their audience, and to support others' roles when performing. By supporting and understanding others, we in turn help ourselves. Using this concept to understand the presentation of self can improve social interactions and create new interpersonal relationships. This knowledge can be used in various social situations, and lead to further understanding others and why we do what we do. If we can understand one another, we can avoid or reduce embarrassment, misunderstanding, and unnecessary aggression in social interactions. By helping others avoid these occurrences, we also help to avoid them for ourselves. Social interactions are what keeps society moving and turning, I would even say they are the essence of society. This is why decreasing the occurrence of misunderstanding, embarrassment and unnecessary aggression is so important. In theory, the knowledge of this concept and its application to the real world could improve the fluidity of the inner workings of society.

The current established belief in America is that if there were classes, the middle class, or the people of America, hold the power of the economy, the government and have equal access to all opportunities. This is a belief that the majority holds more power than the minority, the top 1% of Americans, in all aspects of life. This however, as both Mantsios and Domhoff have written extensively about, is not the reality of our world. As both writers in their articles, “Class in America,” and “Domination Theory of Power,” respectively, debunk and connect data to reveal that wealth and opportunity distribution is not equal among the social classes. Mantsios debunks this myth by going over several different “cases” of middle-class Americans that each make vastly different amounts of money but would consider themselves “middle class.” The most striking difference is the difference in opportunities for success and wealth given to the man that made 300k a year and came from a wealthy family vs that of the opportunities given to the man that came from a family that made more than 50% of Americans, and the opportunities that a black woman from just above the poverty line had. The richest man had several properties and went to prestigious private schools where he grew up with the sons and daughters of prominent figures and made it into an Ivy League school and managed to end up an executive at a corporation in New York City. While the other two that went to public school in the less well off parts of New York City never had access to the tutoring and job opportunities that the well off man had. Proving that the true upper class of society, the 1%, is able to maintain their position over the majority of American people via the opportunities they are provided in their lives. While in “Domination Theory of Power,” Domhoff continues to prove this point on the monopoly of opportunities by showing how many people in the top 1% of society are a part of the same clubs, organizations, and send their children in the same school so the wealthy stick with the wealthy in terms of education and social spheres. Further showing how difficult it is to break into that class from the outside looking in, especially when both writers reveal that this system is supported not by a third of the country’s wealth, like what might be expected of the 1% to own, but of almost 40% of America’s wealth is held by the upper class of American society proving that the power does not belong with the majority, but with the minority in terms of wealth and opportunities.
The United States holds a shared belief perpetuated in our collective consciousness that we live in a classless, equal, society where power is held by the majority middle class. This, is far from the truth as both opportunities for education and careers and the distribution of wealth is skewed greatly towards the 1% of America that truly hold the power.

For centuries, society has had gender norms. The men were in power, the women were beneath them, and most of the time, submitted to the man and his needs. Even thousands of years later, the foundations of the United States only had a group of men writing the Constitution, the foundation of a country, allowing for a bias that has now been normalized in societies. In the past couple decades, the world has been working on correcting the systemic racism, stigma in mental health, women in power, and with finding better ways of accepting those who identify in the LGBTQ2+ community. People in the LGBTQ2+ community often act and look differently than the gender roles and norms that society puts on them. This often results in upset and angry people who believe in tradition and are uncomfortable with change. These people are often hiding their homophobia, sexism, and other forms of hatred and end up hurting people in this community. There are several types of abuse that are often seen to be more prevalent for teens in the community than those who are straight. Most common, sexual trauma. Sexual trauma is reported by many to be a much higher percentage by those who identify in the community, and most of them also admitting it happened in their young, crucial, formative years. For clarity, there is no significant correlation that sexual trauma will not determine a person’s sexuality, but instead that those in the community are more vulnerable to these types of abuse. In this paper, I will be explaining the effect on teens who are in the community that have defied and stood up against gender norms, and the consequences that many teens, who are still children, are facing daily, just because of who they are. These teens who are still trying to figure out life in general are also fighting to figure themselves out, while also having to live by the traditional gender norms and “doing gender”. 
“Doing Gender” is the idea that you will live your life while being assessed by society and the people that surround you, even if they don’t know you. This is often associated with gender norms and the stereotypes that men and women are separately supposed to fulfill. Activities and outward appearances with masculine features, like walking people across the street or carrying something heavy are considered a man’s job, while sitting and looking pretty is more for a female. Females aren’t expected to be loud or dress a certain way because it seems manly, but skirts aren’t correct for men because its “feminine”. These types of gender roles seem minimal, but since it has been engrained in our brains and society, it has become a tradition that many people are unwilling to change, leading to different types of violence. Next, I will be sharing a couple of personal stories of those I know in the community who have been abused and witnessed violence because of the fact that they were subject to gender norms.
*Names have been changed to protect the privacy of those who allowed me to use their stories*
Annie’s Story: Annie had grown up in a very Christian conservative household. No sex, no lying, no cussing, waiting until marriage until you could marry a man. She had a hard time going out on dates because her parents worried about how she may get hurt while she goes out. They were hard on her and expected her to keep up with their strict expectations. Before high school, she had only dated 2 guys. Both of which she didn’t connect too much with, but she thought it may be just because she couldn’t see them often. She went to a private Christian school where she was extremely sheltered. She then transferred to a public high school where the transition was difficult and a brutal culture shock later learning she couldn’t trust everyone she thought she could. She still believed she needed guys for validation because of an abusive home life and not really knowing herself. She trusted one guy who ended up blackmailing her to sexually assault and rape her for over a year. She felt like she couldn’t tell anyone because her offender was black, and her parents were racist. Her parents would not support her, and she couldn’t tell an adult without getting the parents involved since she was still a minor. Her coach noticed her panic attacks when her offender would walk in and figured there was something wrong. Throughout the time, she had to find peace and a home somewhere else. She allowed vulnerability with dating women and is now bisexual. She has told me that this is where she feels safe. She is now in college, away from her parents, where her roommates accept her, and she has noted how much better her mental health has been since she has been in college. I asked her if she ever acted differently or dressed differently around men to keep herself safe, and she didn’t hesitate with saying yes. She will dress more masculine some days or be “one of the boys” so that they won’t try and do what happened to her during her freshmen and sophomore year of high school. She has stated that there have been men who harass her for not being feminine and polite like many women are expected to do. 
Reagan’s Story: Reagan had grown up in a very broken home. She grew up in an African cultured home where the father had many wives and felt as though he could do anything at the demise of the women. While growing up in Islam, her father molested her as a child. She was and witnessed being abused and her mother being abused as well. I personally knew her well for the past couple years and have had to pick her up from her home because she didn’t feel safe. Reagan identifies as lesbian and has for as long as she can remember. She also dresses masculine because that’s what is comfortable, and how she feels safer. She has been through several therapists, medications, and attempts to end her life. Her family does not accept her for not being feminine and not dating men and it something she struggles with every day. She has had sisters who have had arranged marriages with men and is hoping to break this cycle of the gender norm that the female is expected to submit to the man and live to work for his pleasure at home. 
In history, those who did not follow the standard of being straight and doing what traditions told them to, have been redefining gender roles, but against a brutal force. Many people in the community have been seen as not real men or women due to the fact they don’t follow the set gender roles that are aligned with their genitalia. Many gender transgressors are marked in society and deal with intense abuse including verbal and physical violence, scrutiny, and community gossip. Harari connection to Goffman’s Presentation of Self
Self is an interesting concept which has been discussed in this course through many different perspectives. In 21 Lessons for the 21st Century, Harari discusses many topics that connect to sociology. The concept that connects to previous readings we did in class was the concept about self. Harari discusses that homosapians are story tellers and like to see life through a story. “We hope to find meaning by fitting ourselves into some ready-made story about the universe” (p. 302) He continues to say, “There is a storyteller in my mind that explains who I am, where I come from, where I am heading and what is happening to me right now” (p. 305) This can relate to Erving Goffman’s concept, The Presentation of Self. “These attributes of the individual qua performer are not merely a depicted effect of particular performances; they are psychobiological in nature, and yet they seem out of the intimate interaction with the contingency of staging performances.” (Goffman, p. 256)
Erving Goffman, The Presentation of Self, believes that we are actors in our own life. Our life is a stage and we are performers. However, our performances depend on the people involved. The people in our shows create what the social situation is and how we connect to the world. This can change by the way the other people are acting.  “As performers, we are merchants of mortalities. Our day is given over to intimate contact with the goods we display and our minds are filled with intimate understandings of them” (Goffman, p. 255-256) As you can see Goffman sees the concept of self as performers.  He uses the concept that life is a stage and people are acting in the play.  The stage depends on the people, place and what is happening. This creates how people act. Sometimes, other actors create our responses and dictate the play while other times we do the controlling of the show.  
Although these concepts are not exactly the same, they compliment each other.  Harari believes that , “in order to understand ourselves, a crucial step is to acknowledge that the “self” is a fictional story that the intricate mechanisms of our mind constantly manufacture, update and rewrite” (Harari, p. 305). Both believe that people’s lives tell a story but the story is created by how people see themselves or respond to others.  When someone is telling a memory, s/he is telling how they perceived the situation.  Harari says that the story does not need to be complete but it must have two parts to the story. The story “must give me some role to play” (Harari, p. 280). “The story must provide me with an identity and give meaning to my life by embedding me within something bigger than myself” (Harari, p. 280). The Alienation of the Blue-Collar Worker
	In modern society, an individual is defined by their career. Careers determine if one is educated, successful, or just another machine in society. The crossing of alienation and social class reflects society and its perception of an individual. In modern society, individuals look down upon people who work blue-collar jobs and idolize those who are millionaires with their own businesses. The correlation between social class and alienation reflects the imbalance of power and opportunities that shape individuals’ experiences and identities.
	Social class divides society into economic groups, resulting in resource discrepancies and shaping overall life experiences. In the historical and modern world, labor workers experience a different lifestyle to those of wealth and status. Labor workers have worked endless hours to make ends meet, make insufficient salaries, and work in harsh conditions yet receive no recognition. Those of wealth, however, receive all recognition of the work of the labor workers. Praised by all in society, the wealthy class receives all the economic benefits that result in access to education, the ability to move up the socioeconomic ladder, and guarantee a successful lifestyle for their children. 
	A prime example of the discrepancies in lifestyles in today's society is the family of a trade worker and the family of a businessman. Social media has allowed society to view different lifestyles, especially TikTok. TikTok has allowed individuals to post their day to day lives, allowing viewers to get the reality of their life. In a day to day of trade worker, the day begins at seven am and ends at five pm. In between their days, trade workers are expected to work in the blazing heat and meet job expectations with little to no help outside of their work crew. Alongside many trade workers work under 1099. They are expected to buy the tools and necessities to complete the job but receive no benefits from their jobs. Trade workers are required to search for and pay for healthcare on their own and at times for their families as well resulting in the need to work countless hours. Whereas the life of a businessman sounds bliss compared to the life of a trade worker.  They can work a nine-to-five job, have access to healthcare, and receive an abundance of benefits. This is later reflected in the interactions they have with their own families. 
	As trade workers work countless hours to make ends meet for their families, their jobs become their identifying factors. There are no longer any separating factors between who the trade worker is as a person and his job. Children begin to view their parents as concrete workers rather than fathers or mothers. Trade workers start to invest in their careers in hopes of economic prosperity resulting in the lack of quality family time. Business owners, however, have the luxury to separate themselves from their jobs. They can practice hobbies, cut time out of their day to spend time with their family, and invest in their family rather than their careers. Business owners do not have the need to alienate themselves for their jobs and have it be a describing factor to who they are as a person. They now instead can focus on obtaining resources that guarantee long-lasting economic success for their children whether it's an investment in their education or hobbies. They have the privilege of becoming known as the family man rather than the working man. However, this success of identification is only granted through the imbalance of power between the two. 
	The trade worker does not have the luxury of working on their own time and merit compared to the businessman. In the capitalist world, there must always be a worker generating revenue for the ‘boss’. The ‘boss’ will take the revenue generated and distribute a portion of it to pay their workers. Though the ‘boss’ did not partake in any of the labor, they gained all the means and the labor workers must now rely on the generosity of their boss. The trade worker no longer works for themselves, creating work that they are passionate about, but instead, work to create products for the ‘boss’ further alienating themselves. Thus, resulting in greater power and economic imbalance between the two classes. 
	The relationship between alienation and social class reveals the complex ties between the imbalance of power and opportunities that lead to the individuals' identity. Through the difference in lifestyles, the identities of trade workers are vastly different from the businessman. With the businessman having access to an abundance of resources that guarantee economic prosperity, allowing them to find identifying factors outside of their career. Whereas the trade worker does not have economic security, forcing them to revolve their lives around their job. The difference in economic security further perpetuates the power imbalance between the two. As one has more economic freedom than the other, allows the businessman to work for themselves in comparison to the trade worker working for the businessman. Recognizing the imbalance of power and opportunities allows the potential to demand change and move toward an equal society, in which one does not have to alienate themselves for their career, and social class does not determine the long-lasting success of an individual.

The Effects of Artificial Intelligence on the Consciousness of Self
	In modern society, the advancements of artificial intelligence are developing at an exponential rate. Micheal Haenlein and Andreas Kaplan define artificial intelligence as “a system’s ability to interpret external data correctly, to learn from such data, and to use those learnings to achieve specific goals and tasks through flexible adaptation”. As this artificial intelligent technology evolves, children are growing up in a world where it is not uncommon to rely on computers for everyday needs. Because of this, people are becoming more reliant than ever on machines. The reliance on AI is a newly found concept that continues to grow, becoming more powerful than we can imagine. With a world becoming so dependent on highly intelligent technology systems, one could consider what the outcome would be if this technology were to disappear. One could also consider what the outcome would be if technology were to completely take over. What would happen to humanity's ability to function? 
	As time goes on, and the electronic world flourishes, an individual's ability to be self-aware is being quickly depreciated. The consciousness of self is the idea that one is not only aware of their surroundings, but they are aware of how they feel, how they are perceived, and who they are in general. The consciousness of self can be interpreted in many different ways from many different theorists. It is important for one to be connected to their consciousness of self because it helps to express one's individuality. With artificial intelligence developing to the vast size that it is today, great change is happening without humanity even knowing. Artificial intelligence has negative effects on one’s perception of self because it limits one's ability to have original ideas, puts individuals at risk of job loss, makes one blindly reliant, causes one to be unaware of their surroundings, and decreases the amount of social interaction in general. 
	Individuality is one aspect that is heavily affected by the growth of artificial intelligence. One can argue that today, there is less original thought being provoked because everybody is fed the same information. Being fed the same information makes it extremely difficult for people to form their own ideas and opinions simply because they are given the right answer with no additional thought. As the world is being rewritten by AI, the human race adapts, because that is our nature. In Our Identities in The Age of Artificial Intelligence, Jun Wu states “These impacts will prompt us to adapt. In the process, our identities will shift. For example, workers who thrived performing repetitive tasks will see their jobs being replaced by AI systems. In those instances, the workers’ identities and how they perceive themselves will need to shift with their changing environment… we will need to naturally shift our own social identities to adapt to this new world.” (Wu 3)  This shows that people will adapt to whatever the circumstances may be. In this case, individuals will adapt to a society with no original thought. With no individuality, it would not only directly affect the way a society would function, but would essentially strip people of their identities and everyone will be the same.
With the advancements of artificial intelligence, social interaction is put at high risk. If society fully replaced human to human interaction, with human to artificial intelligence interaction, society would lack real, personal connections. In Can Social Interaction Constitute Social Cognition, Hanne De Jaegher, Ezequiel Di Paolo, and Shaun Gallagher states “A definition of social interaction should capture these intuitions concerning the engagement of at least two agents in a complex co-regulated pattern. Engagement can correspond to fluctuating feelings of connectedness with the other – whose meaning sometimes seems transparent and sometimes opaque – and of increasing and decreasing possibilities for participation. This experience sometimes turns into that of being taken up in the flow of the interaction” (Jaegher et al. 442) This shows that an interaction should provide a sense of connectedness. By connecting and building strong ties with family, friends and the community, people tend to feel a sense of security, support, and purpose. George Herbert Mead believed that the conceptualization of ourselves can be broken into two parts: the “me” and the “I”. The “me” regulates our behavior based on how we think that others perceive us, while the “I” is the reaction caused from the attitude of a community. Mead believes the conceptualization of ourselves are defined through the interactions encountered in the social realm. Adolescence is an important time to build social skills and form identity, but with the substitution of AI interaction for real-life interaction, teens will experience major impacts on their social and emotional development. 
Human interaction is extremely important for one to understand and perceive their own self. Erving Goffman discovered that the self is collectively produced in the Presentation of Self. He proves that human interaction is so complex that roles are created within a society to provide purpose. Presentation of Self elaborated on the idea of roles in a set society by directly dividing an individual into two parts: the performer and the character. “...the very structure of the self can be seen in terms of how we arrange for such performances in our Anglo-American society” (Goffman 256). This entails that the social world is made up through an abundance of performances by an enormous amount of actors, in a variation of settings. Erving Goffman proposes that we find our identities through the process of performing and observing the way we execute the performance. In “How AI will rewire us”, Nicholas A. Christakis states “But adding artificial intelligence to our midst could be much more disruptive. Especially as machines are made to look and act like us and to insinuate themselves deeply into our lives, they may change how loving or friendly or kind we are—not just in our direct interactions with the machines in question, but in our interactions with one another.” (Christakis 1) This directly shows the potential threat that artificial intelligence brings upon a community. Adding AI to a social environment can only cause humans to behave differently, whether it be shown through daily social skills or something as simple as productivity. 
The current technological improvements regarding AI, have created a widespread fear of job loss.  After looking at whose specific job is at risk it is important to consider the numbers, how many jobs are being taken? Arto Baltayan, technology writer and technical documentations specialist stated in his article, “Robots, Automation and Technology Taking Over-- Is Your Job At Risk?”, “Between 2000 and 2010, the United States lost over five-and-a-half million jobs in the manufacturing sector,” (Baltayan 1) This shows that the amount of jobs being lost in the United States is extremely high, on top of that, all this evidence is only talking about one sector. Moreover, artificial intelligence technology is not just affecting employees in manufacturing, but has a significant effect on all jobs. William M. Rodgers, professor of public policy at Rutgers University stated “Yet most analysis tends to be prospective in nature, and estimates of future impacts on employment vary widely, with some studies predicting that as many as 50 percent of all workers are at risk of losing their jobs to automation.” (Rodgers 1) This shows that the integration of artificial intelligence does not only impact the manufacturing sector, but has a broader effect on all aspects of the workforce contributing to the predicted 50 percent of all workers losing their jobs to artificial intelligence technology. Without a given purpose, an individual faces the threat of a perception and identity crisis. If artificial intelligence learns how to possess a higher consciousness to function with human behaviors and habits, the people will be forced to learn how to adapt to a new technological world. 
Human beings are conscious not only of the world around them but also of themselves: their activities, their bodies, and their mental lives. Changes to consciousness can result in changes in perception, thinking, understanding, and interpretations of the world. In “Society, consciousness and change—An inquiry into Pentti Malaska's futures thinking”, Markku Malaska states “The dynamics of development, where extensive and intensive stages alternate at the same time as regenerative growth forces development into a specific direction.” (Malaska 61) This can be applied to the effects of artificial intelligence because these technological advancements are a major change that will bring upon an inevitable outcome. Adding artificial intelligence to a social environment, will eventually lead to a change in the way society performs. This initially starts with a single individual and their cognition processes being altered by the outside factor. One may ask, if the addition of AI will only bring upon questionable change, why do it? In The impact of artificial intelligence on human society and bioethics, Michael Cheng-Tek Tai states “History tells us that human is always looking for something faster, easier, more effective, and convenient to finish the task they work on; therefore, the pressure for further development motivates humankind to look for a new and better way of doing things.” (Tai 1) This is able to explain the motives behind developing a human society. As the human race has the ability to raise their consciousness higher, they tend to strive for more, without consideration of the possible consequences.  
Overall, it can be shown that artificial intelligence can have negative effects on one’s perception of self due to a multitude of reasons. One being the limitations placed on one’s ability to create their own ideas and opinions. Without the influence of others original thoughts and ideas, there would be no free expression and individuality. Individuality is very important when it comes to the consciousness of one’s self. This is because one feels a sense of reassurance in knowing that they have an idea of who they are, or what their identity consists of. A major contributing factor to one’s sense of purpose, that should not go unmentioned, would be the type of job or position that one hold’s. When an individual lacks a sense of purpose, they become susceptible to a loss of self-awareness. Artificial intelligence is not able to raise it’s consciousness like humans, but once it is able to expand its potential, many will fear for their jobs. This will essentially lead to a dependence on artificial intelligence. With a society reliant on AI, many traits of independence and self-sufficiency will deteriorate. The consciousness of self is heavily affected by the surrounding community. One may even say, the consciousness of self can develop solely from the environmental factors one is exposed to. With a heavy reliance on artificial intelligence, social interaction will eventually lose the personal connection and meaning. We find our identities through the process of performing and observing the way we execute our performance.

Racial Bias in the Criminal Justice System in America
The rate of imprisonment in the United States has seen a five times increase since 1972 and 40% of those prisoners are Black. This may come as a surprise since Black Americans make up only 13% of the population, but there is evidence to suggest that those numbers are engineered by a corrupt Criminal Justice system. For every 100,000 Black Americans, 2,306 of them are incarcerated. Compare that to white Americans, where for every 100,000 there are 450 incarcerated individuals, and you begin to see a trend (Sakala 2014). In light of recent events in the news, like the trial of Derek Chauvin for the murder of George Floyd, more people than ever are talking about police brutality and the Criminal Justice system. The racism goes farther than police brutality, however, and it infects even the deepest roots of our prison system. The American Criminal Justice System does not just passively perpetuate systematic racism in the United States through the personal prejudices of a few police officers, but rather it is founded and based upon discrimination as an inherent mechanism by which it operates. The War on Drugs, mass incarceration, police brutality, and wrongful convictions are all integral to the oppression seen by this system. 
	White Privilege by Peggy McIntosh outlines several things, 26 to be exact, that are daily occurrences of White Privilege that white people rarely think about being a privilege. White people have the privilege of not having their communities ravaged during the War on Drugs. White people have the privilege of simply existing around police officers without fearing for their safety because of the color of their skin. White people have the privilege of not losing their mothers, fathers, brothers, and sisters all to a prison system that incarcerates them at a higher rate than people of different skin color. White people have the privilege of having a fair and just trial, where they do not know in the back of their minds that people of their skin color are being wrongfully put to death and imprisoned at a higher rate than any other skin color. These things are all happening behind the scenes, but are very purposeful in their effect on Black communities. 
	“We knew we couldn’t make it illegal to be either against the war or black, but by getting the public to associate the hippies with marijuana and blacks with heroin, and then criminalizing both heavily, we could disrupt those communities. We could arrest their leaders, raid their homes, break up their meetings, and vilify them night after night on the evening news. Did we know we were lying about the drugs? Of course, we did” (Baum 2016). This quote said by John Ehrlichman, who was the Assistant to Domestic Affairs of President Richard Nixon, shows how deep racism runs in the War on Drugs. The War on Drugs was not the first or only instance of Black people being wrongly blamed for an ongoing drug problem in the United States (Lusane, and Desmond 1991). In the late 1880s, cocaine was being included in everything from medicine to soft drinks and cigarettes. By 1906, the Pure Food and Drug Act was passed which required any product manufacturer to tell consumers that their products contained addictive drugs or substances. A few years later in 1909, Dr. Hamilton Wright would be chosen by President Theodore Roosevelt to lead a campaign to stop the opium trade in Asia. In 1910, he would release the Report on the International Opium Commission, which proved to employ racist imagery and scapegoating to appeal to the racism of white Americans. The report would include lies about Black people, even going as far as to propose that cocaine use made them bulletproof, gave them unimaginable strength, and, worst of all, encouraged them to rape women. This was a blatant lie, as no evidence at the time suggested that Black men used cocaine at a higher rate than any other demographic. These lies had disastrous effects, resulting in the “Red Summer” of 1919 where almost seventy lynchings were recorded (Lusane, and Desmond 1991).
 Over the next decade, many more decisions would be made to undermine Black communities in America. The Mafia, with their ever-growing power in the 1950s, decided to sell hard drugs almost exclusively to Black Americans. This decision created a Heroin addiction epidemic of intense proportions which disproportionally affected Black communities. Over many years of struggling with addiction, Black communities would turn to drug dealing and gangs to at least make some money off of their growing drug problem. The government’s solution to this problem was vastly more destructive than helpful. Instead of understanding the root of the drug problem in Black neighborhoods, the solution was to build prisons and fill them with said Black neighborhoods (Lusane, and Desmond 1991).  This leads to the next mechanism used by the criminal justice system to undermine Black communities in the United States: mass incarceration. 
According to a report released by The Sentencing Project in 1994, one in three Black American men ages 20-29 is under the control of the criminal justice system, meaning in prison, on parole, or on probation (Mauer, and Huling 1995). As stated previously, Black Americans make up 40% of the prison population while only making up 13% of the American population. The logical conclusion is not that Black Americans do more crime, but rather that the laws are affecting them disproportionately. The cities that regularly house the poorest and most vulnerable citizens are also the most paroled, and as a result, produce more incarcerations. The judgment cannot necessarily be made that these neighborhoods have more crime happening in them, just that preconceived notions influence increased rates of police intervention (Fagan et al. 2003). As much of the effect incarceration has on the actual individuals being incarcerated, it is also worth noting that families of these individuals may bear more of the hardships of their families being ripped apart from the inside out. When you take into account fathers and mothers leaving children to grandparents, children going into the foster system, and children turning to sell drugs as a way to survive, the cycle continues exponentially (Braman 2003). It was previously determined that drug laws disproportionately affect Black Americans, and these drug laws are working to strip defendants of their rights to a fair trial. The judicial system works to ‘overcharge’ defendants to effectively scare them into waiving their rights to trial by pleading guilty. This causes the majority, more than 90% in some cases, of drug-related cases being ended by guilty pleas rather than a trial (Roberts 2008).
 	Mass incarceration leads to a disproportionately high number of Black felons. Felons are stripped of their rights to vote or bear arms. Felons also may not be able to travel freely, are barred from employment in some fields, and may lose parental rights to any children they may have and may not participate in many forms of public aid like food stamps and public housing ("What Rights Do Convicted Felons Lose?"). In modern prison systems, all felons are stripped of these rights, but it wasn’t always this way. In the late 1860s, some Southern states passed laws to punish crimes by removing their rights to vote, but they were assigned to crimes like burglary, thievery, adultery, and those convicted of domestic violence, all of which were mainly committed by Black people. Those convicted of murder, however, were not stripped of their right to vote. It can only be assumed that is because more white people were convicted of murder than Black people (Roberts 2008).
There is yet another angle to view this from, however, if we consider that Black Americans are being incarcerated and prosecuted at a higher rate than white Americans, we can also infer that there is a higher percentage of Black Americans being wrongfully accused as well. As of October 2016, Black Americans make up 47% of exonerations listed in the National Registry of Exonerations (Gross et al. 2017). This is not even taking into account the 1,800 people who were framed for crimes as a part of several large scandals, later set straight with “group exonerations.” Innocent Black Americans are seven times more likely to be falsely accused of murder and three-and-a-half times more likely to be falsely accused of sexual assault. They are also five times more likely to be arrested for illegal drug-related crimes, despite using drugs at the same rates as white Americans. Black people are more likely to be stopped and searched concerning drug crimes than white Americans, which is already determined to be deadly in some cases of police brutality. There have even been cases of police officers blatantly lying to incarcerate Black people for drug-related crimes. In 1999 Tom Coleman, an undercover narcotics officer, framed 39 people, most being Black, for selling cocaine. In 2003, 35 of those people were found innocent and Coleman was found guilty of perjury. The cocaine that he proposed was being sold by these people came from cocaine that he owned and bought (Gross et al. 2017).
 Police officers have long brought violence to Black communities and often serve as judge, jury, and executioner for many. The media representation of the Derek Chauvin trial has thrown police brutality into the minds of more American’s than ever, but his trial is something that many Black Americans do not have the privilege to be a part of. The criminal justice system works hard to convince the American public that these are isolated events of bad people doing bad things, rather than inherent and systematic racism ingrained in the very fibers of every police uniform worn in this country. Police officers choose to protect other police officers, rather than choosing to protect and serve the people they promised they would, this is often called “the blue wall of silence” (Roberts 2008).  If we cannot trust the very people who are entrusted to uphold and enforce our laws to not allow their prejudices to influence who they arrest, who can we trust? The answer is that we should have never trusted these officers in the first place because they are products of an entire system that was built to produce people with the power over life and death and to give them those prejudices.
After outlining four distinct ways the criminal justice system strives to undermine and poison Black communities in America, it is obvious that the system has less of a passive role in systematic racism and more of a foundational and oppressive role. The War on Drugs, dating back to far before Nixon or Reagan’s presidency, simultaneously spread horrible rumors about Black Americans and their role in the growing drug problem in the early 1990s, and later got Black communities dependent on heroin. Mass incarceration put many Black Americans back into the exploitive prison labor system, reminiscent of slavery work conditions, tore apart their families and communities, and lead to the over-policing of Black neighborhoods that we still struggle heavily with. Black Americans who were convicted of felonies also lose a lot of their rights, most devastatingly, the right to public aid that would help to support their families as well as being able to be employed in several fields. This further ruins Black communities and allows young Black people to grow up in unstable situations, completely out of their control. Wrongful convictions affect Black Americans at a higher rate than white Americans and therefore contribute in their own way to the destruction of Black communities and their ways of life. Police officers are allowed and encouraged by the criminal justice system to assume that Black people are violent and a danger to them and others. This must be recognized as a system that was built on the oppression of Black people and not just an unfortunate byproduct. As slavery was made illegal, America turned to “separate-but-equal.” As that was outlawed, lawmakers and public officials found entirely new ways to ensure that Black Americans would never be equal. These have no place in modern America and the system by which they are allowed to continue happening has to be reformed or abolished before any more damage is done to Black communities in America.

Social Media and the Power Elite’s Influence on Politics
America has not had the traditional forms of power held for most of its existence. As when compared to Europe, there has not any singular church to rule over the country as was the case in Europe for centuries, or a very large government to hold all the power as it was with nation-states in Europe or an extremely powerful military that could threaten to overthrow the government until very recently in 1940, relatively recent in the scope of 1776 to now. As G. William Domhoff points out then, there is only one way in which power can be accumulated in America, gaining economic power. This through the years has created its own social class of power elites in America that doesn’t put these people in positions as public policymakers like congressmen and women, but as corporate executives and members of the 1% that begin to decide everything through social circles that tend to involve board members of 80%-90% of all corporations in the United States. 
These corporations while at first may have been limited to a few large media companies like big television networks like NBC and ABC and big newspapers like the LA Times and New York Times, the power elite’s control over the media has grown since then. With the boom of the internet and social media over the past 20 years, the power elite has been put in a  better position to influence public policy and the general public’s opinion on policy through the usage of algorithms that have been put in place on social media like on Facebook which has created polarization on both sides of political debates.
G. William Domhoff defines in his work, “Power in America,” the three indicators of power as who benefits, who governs, and who wins. In these indicators, the corporate executives are able to hold positions of economic power that they financially benefit from. But also benefit from the political power they are able to hold in the usage of their funds for donations to campaigns of candidates that they either already influence or align with the beliefs of the power elite in turn putting the power elite in charge of the policymaking process allowing them to govern. As mentioned before, Domhoff points out that 15-20% of corporate directors that sit on 2 or more boards of directors that make up 80% to 90% of the largest corporations in the US into what is a very well-connected corporate community. Facebook, Twitter, and Instagram consist of these very large corporations now and likely have board members that are part of the “inner circle” 15-20% that influence the entire corporate community. This allows the corporations and in turn, the power elite to put who they desire in office to put in policies that benefit these large corporations and 1% of society more than the majority of Americans meaning that these power elites continue to win with those they put into office.
How does the power elite manage to win over public opinion on policies that should seem clear to not benefit the general public that is actually in control of the election process in America? This is where the influence of social media comes into play for politics. In an article written by Taiana Bucher, she evaluates the new algorithms that Facebook is putting into place and how these algorithms create misleading information to users in terms of the news they believe they are receiving. In her article, Bucher points out that Facebook models its homepage so that down the middle is a column titled, “News Feed” which is split into two types of Top News and Most Recent. Top News is what is primarily shown in the News Feed which the algorithm for determining what is, “Top News” is related to pages people interact with the most and like the most. Misleading the readers then to think that everything that pops up in their News Feed is the actual News when in reality, it is just news catered to your interests which can lead to the common misinformation we regularly read about when someone ends up only interacting with news sources of one political viewpoint. This is how the power elite gains public support for policymakers that would not normally be supported by the people. Passive misinformation can happen this way where the target audiences the power elite wants to reach can use this algorithm and others like it on other social media platforms to have users engage with news sources that consistently pump out information those users agree with and could spin that information to have that policymaker sound like they agree with what the general public wants.
This has put America on a trajectory where information and news are not dictated by fact, but by those who have the most engagement on their respective social media sites. This is a future that Stephan Lewandowsky and his other writers in their article about the era they labeled as the “post-truth” era have laid out and also fear that we are going towards. Lewandowsky and the other writers of the article look to the 2016 presidential election to show that this is already been proven to have worked with the popularity of what is said is more valued more than what is true. As they cite that an independent fact-checker known as PolitiFact found that during their respective campaigns, 70% of all statements made by Donald Trump were false as compared to the 26% of all statements made by Hillary Clinton during the campaign were false. Yet, Donald Trump was elected president of the United States over Hilary Clinton which Lewandowsky et. al. point to the fact that pro-Trump statements on Twitter were 4 times as prevalent as pro-Clinton statements on Twitter due to active efforts by pro-Trump Tweetbots that managed to skyrocket Trump’s interaction with the algorithm to get more viewership and in turn popularity on Twitter than what might be anticipated. Trump exists as one of the most obvious symbols of the power elite, who has been a one-percenter since the 1980s and has been the face of American wealth for over 40 years as a business executive. As a member of the power elite and probably a member of those inner circles of the corporate community that dictate the plans that are set into motion by these corporations, Donald Trump knew how to effectively manipulate the algorithms that were set in place to allow the very thing he did, which was win the election, through understanding how to just gain enough popularity through the usage of social media to influence an entire election for the US Presidency. 
This alone is enough of a sign for how we have entered into the “post-truth” era of America. The fact that the highest office in America, which obviously in the past has been influenced by the power elite but never directly held by the power elite, was attainable through manipulation with an algorithm on a website and app used by the majority of American people should be a massive red flag to the people of America. Yes, misinformation can be combatted through diligent solo research on topics important to each individual but that alone is part of the problem. The fact that the people have to actively go out of their way to go to websites and news sources they don’t normally go to, to ensure that they aren’t being misinformed by the information they receive on sites like Twitter and Facebook that is catered to them by the algorithm. If an algorithm has a misinformation problem that literally placed a man from the power elite into the highest office of the United States that did not have the best interests of the majority population of America at heart and even showed it multiple times throughout his campaign, then maybe something should be done about the algorithms, not just the methods Americans should go about getting their information.
Some people have realized the influence that these algorithms can have when controlled in such a manner. That is why as Robert Gorwa writes in his article explaining platform governance, he cites the calls in Europe and many other countries too for these social media platforms to have a form of rules and regulations that must be followed. As it stands right now on the internet, there are no real laws or regulations for social media platforms when it comes to the information they provide, or don’t provide to their users in terms of the news. But, with the explorations in platform governance that Gorwa references, there may soon enough be a model for the United States to base their own platform governance laws on if what is being sought after in the EU is reliable and works to help solve misinformation and polarization issues that are so prevalent on social media platforms.
Social media’s influence cannot be ignored. It has influenced the entire American people through misinformation and the withholding of information that hasn’t ever been seen on this scale before. Yes, the power elite, who have always been in charge of media outlets have never spread misinformation on this level before, but that is because the usage of algorithms and the relative anonymity that is generally present on the internet means that they cannot be held liable largely for what occurs. If misinformation gets blamed for creating presidencies like Donald Trump where other power elites run and win, it can only be blamed on a math equation that was set up to help people see more of what that equation believes each user should see. Whether it was inadvertent or not, an algorithm has been set up across the primary American social media platforms that have been proven to be easily manipulated and when manipulated can jettison a man who nobody thought would ever be president into the highest office of the United States because of, in part, a Twitter algorithm. For better, or for worse these algorithms have significantly changed the lives of Americans, and the sooner we collectively realize the power and influence the algorithms have over us all and the information we do and do not see and that these algorithms are, to some extent, understood by the power elite to the point that they understand how they can be manipulated.
