29 November 2021
Of the Past and Present
From Emile Durkheim, to George Herbert Mead, to Yuval Noah Harari, sociological concepts of the past and today intertwine to create divine thoughts and ideas that challenge one another. No individual sociological thinker is the same because sociology itself is made up of the multitude of minds: creating what we know today as our world and our collective consciousness. Yet there are always inconsistencies – moments of inequities between perspectives that demonstrate how to be a sociological thinker, and how one cannot latch onto a single idea. For myself, it is sometimes hard to grasp and difficult to accept that the ideas I built my life upon were created out of a need for security and a lack of individuality. That goes for religion, collective representation, the authentic self, and the fiction that our world so easily plays into.
Emile Durkheim states that the religion of society is important to study because “the idea of society is the soul of religion” (The Cultural Logic of Collective Representation pg. 72). Durkheim concludes that religious rituals in early Homo sapiens came about from new and untouched emotion from Morotopithecus. As the emotion in our early species was created, it brought with it the capacity for symbolic thought and the connection between the neocortex and the amygdala in psychology. Durkheim believes that by studying patterns of religion in society and how that pattern was created, it is easily viable to see how new types of religions and collective representations can come about. 
Yuval Noah Harari, in his book “21 Lessons for the 21st Century” and specifically in God in Part 3, details how the sociology of today impacts everything we know and do. He acknowledges the work of Karl Marx and many others, concluding that their theses helped to lay the foundation of what our world believes is true, and what we have created out of our minds that is a fallacy. Harari states that humans make God both a “cosmic mystery” and a “worldly lawgiver” (pg. 202). The idea of religion, more specifically God, is such an inconcrete thing, yet we make it the most concrete part of our lives and our collective. Each religious person makes God the answer and explanation to their own ignorance. Harari mentions that religion creates a set of rules that followers must, for lack of a better word, follow to be the best version of themselves that God will accept the most. Yet, these same set of rules also govern what humans are allowed to get away with. Harari uses the example of how some religions believe that drinking alcohol is a sin, yet a Christian woman may say that God said it was okay to have another glass of wine. These inconsistencies within people, and therefore what those people believe in, make religion and what we believe of God to be a rocky subject.
That is not to say that Harari disagrees with the foundations of religion that Durkheim is arguing. In fact, it is fairly correct to say that what Durkheim is arguing about religion being created out of a need for explanations is very much what Harari is qualifying. Yet, the differences in the time period and how much our world has changed throughout the decades, and even longer, reveals distinct thoughts that are separate from each other. Religious institutions that created guidelines to follow are still very much intact today, yet Harari argues that they show no difference than guidelines of government or social entities. “These laws were certainly very helpful in establishing and maintaining the social order for thousands of years. But in that, they are not fundamentally different from the laws of secular states and institutions” (Harari pg. 204). Harari says that to him personally, wondering about the greatest mysteries of the universe has no connection to following a set of guidelines for a leader that were most likely made up by “imaginative Homo sapiens.” 
When considering this about Harari, what he and Durkheim conclude about religion is connected, yet they diverge paths. Durkheim states the collective consciousness is the body that allows religion to thrive and continue because people need something to believe in. Harari is arguing that we may be a more successful community of individuals that can better maintain a social order without a religious entity hanging over us. Considering the collective consciousness, Durkheim believes that the study of religious rituals has further pushed collective life into existence and collective representation, the manifestations of collective consciousness. Harari takes a tone of disapproval towards the collective consciousness, and values its negative effects of how religion and non-secularism has been forced upon the collective society, causing more harm to our mental wellbeing and what our minds can process. Durkheim wants to study why religion is a concept made of thin air, and Harari wants to dispel that same air and dissect it for what it is. Both authors believe that religion is somewhat of a construct, but they individually want to hold that construct accountable in their own particular manners.
According to George Herbert Mead, our persons are separated into two entities: the self or mind and the body. Our body is material, or rather what we can see, while our self is something that cannot be accessed just by looking at it. However, humans cannot get an experience from our whole body, like for example, we cannot see our backs or internal organs. The body does not have the capacity to experience the entirety of itself, but the self is a thing that is constantly open. Our body serves as the object and is incomplete knowledge, but our self can be both object and subject and is being constantly communicated. The parts that constitute the self, or rather make it up, are known as the “me” and the “I.” “I” is what humans say in direct response to outward communication and is the subject, where “me” is the mindset, a human has in responding to themselves and serves as the object. The “me” shows similarities to James’ Social Selves concepts. “Me” is what is born out of the collective consciousness, and an example of this would be a student wanting to raise their hand because of “I,” but their “me” says that the answer may be too trivial or political.
Science fiction is a concept that humans are remarkably familiar with. It is incredibly common to flip channels on the TV and find battles between robots and aliens, or crazy machines that travel to different dimensions. Humans enjoy this type of genre because we are the only species on earth that can understand the concept of fiction and therefore further communicate it. Harari highlights that the main problem that comes with fiction, but specifically in Part 4 with Science Fiction, is that it “confuses intelligence with consciousness” (Harari pg. 253). In movie scenarios, Harari states that there is always the main character who has a layer of their authentic self that “remains untouched” from the bindings of the “matrix” and “technological manipulations” (pg. 254). The cliché of movies creates a protagonist that watchers are drawn to because of the unlocked and untouchable part of themselves. The movie ends with the main character breaking out of said bindings and finding his own authenticity, which he then realizes has just been a myth created by the even greater “matrix” that is real life.
Both Mead and Harari explain that each human individual has a “self” that is the innermost and realest part of ourselves. It is something that we can access, but of course is very personal and sometimes difficult to comprehend. However, this authenticity that we believe to be untouched is still socially structured. “There is no authentic self waiting to be liberated from the manipulative shell (Harari pg. 254)” because there is no authentic self – it has already been manipulated. Our minds have no distinction between external cultural systems that we are a part of and internal beliefs that we hold. Mead and Harari qualify that we are subject to thinking that a part of ourselves is authentic because it agrees with the security we need to survive and have meaning in life. Science Fiction aims to explain that humans are constantly avoiding being trapped within the confinements of society, yet the confinement occurs from the human brain and from our own control. We are the “matrix” and therefore are what we fear being a part of. Our “self” is both the object and the subject, and therefore it is subject to the authenticity we create within it. 
Durkheim and Mead have both immensely delved into how the human brain’s symbolic thought has led it to create an authenticity that is impacted by external factors, and therefore is an internal subject. Durkheim mentions that the collective consciousness of society exists independently from humans and provides us with categories of thought to understand and follow. The collective consciousness forms moral values that we follow to be considered an individual that is accepted within society. Our “I” and “me” factor into how we are and how we want the rest of our community to see us, which are two very separate concepts. The mind-body duality and emotions that brought about religious rituals are still relevant in present time, showing that as society evolves, it does not always change.
Harari’s Part 3 and 4 of his analytical novel stretch the thought processes from what we have learned from sociological thinkers like Durkheim and Mead into how we understand our minds and external world today. He underscores that God in every religion is a divided belief of a superhero and triumphant leader, and that concepts of science fiction often have deeper meaning, like everything else in society. He connects all his ideas together in a formative matter that leaves the reader able to question everything they know about their life: the good and the bad. He challenges and negates the collective consciousness and encourages everyone to strive for a world that we create with individuality and diversity.
Our sociology modules have given me the ability to change how I see society, how to better fix it for tomorrow, and learn to understand that not everything we believe is a reality. Sociology demonstrates how humans are cogs in a broken clock, but if that clock is built for something different, our lives may have more fulfillment. Thanks to Durkheim, Mead, and Harari, we can better reveal how the security and individuality that we so often strive for within the society we live in is missing key components: truth and humanity.

The Impact of Social Media on the Young Selves
	In 2014 for my 12th birthday my parents bought me the black LG Cosmos 3 slider phone. The only functions were texts, calls, and a brick breaker game. Owning that phone gave me a small insight to what I believed adulthood was like, however, it could not show me what the adults at the time were doing, thinking, saying, or even wearing. The phone itself was the symbol of adulthood, rather than what the phone provided. Fast forward to 2020, I was entering my senior year of highschool, and my youngest sister, Heidi, was entering sixth grade. Rather than getting a slider phone like I had, she got a new iPhone 8. Over the span of just six years, the representation of a phone had completely changed. Heidi was excited, yet it wasn’t even that big of a deal, all of her friends already had phones, in which they had access to thousands of different applications they could download. Of those apps, the most prevalent ones proved to be social media. My sister instantly had access to the lives of not just her friends, but also her acquaintances, distant family, celebrities, and thousands of others. In today’s society, access to the information social media holds forces younger generations to mature quicker, and negatively impacts the constituents that define the Self. 
	The changes I noticed in my sister after having a phone were outstanding compared to the changes I had after receiving my first phone. I barely changed, I still wore the same clothes, talked the same way, and had the same friends within a year of owning my first phone. Heidi, on the other hand started wearing completely different clothes, obtained many new friends, stopped talking to many others, completely changed the decorations and color of her room, got a very different haircut, and even had a large change in her everyday vocabulary, only in the first year of owning her phone. Along with the outstanding changes in her lifestyle, Heidi also obtained vast amounts of knowledge about society, including current events, the clothes people wear, the language adults use, to the shows and movies people watch, the places her friends go and the things they do, and so much more. All these changes and gained knowledge can be accounted for by the use of social media. 
	The intention of social media is to share what you do in your daily life, aiming to cultivate friendships and decrease loneliness, but the harsh reality of social media demonstrates vast differences from this purpose.The knowledge Heidi has been exposed to along with the changes she has undergone have taken a significant toll on her mental health. Her life on social media and her life in the real world intertwined, and has given her symptoms of anxiety and even depression at her young age. Social media has caused her to develop personality issues, the constituents that make up her sense of ‘self’ have been negatively impacted by the use of social media. 
	William James, famous philosopher, historian, and psychologist, loosely defines the Self as “all that he CAN call his, not only his body and his psychic, but his clothes and his house, his wife and children, his ancestors and friends, his reputation and works, his lands and horses, and yacht and bank account.” The Self is made up of several different aspects, but can be separated into four general constituents; the material self, the social self, the spiritual self, and the pure ego. By becoming aware of the feelings and emotions these constituents arouse, along with “the actions to which they prompt” (James 123), one can understand the self in its widest sense. 
	The constituents that make up the self each have their own impact on personality and the way we and others view ourselves. The material self is made up of many aspects, but “the body is the innermost part of the material Self in each of us” (James 123). Other aspects of the material self are what we consider a part of us, this includes close family and friends, the home we live in, to the clothes we wear and the commodities we earned with labor. The material self is one of the largest factors in determining and expressing our personality and Self. 
	Next is the social self which is “the recognition [one] gets from his mates” (James 123). The social self is a factor people find most important, but also the most stressful. The social self is how we interact with others, as well as how others see us. “A man has as many social selves as there are individuals who recognize him and carry an image of them in their mind” (James 123). The social self is very influential on the personality others believe we have, and your social self can vary greatly among the people you’ve interacted with. The social self fluctuates the most among the other aspects, and determines our personality to others.
	The spiritual self, on the other hand, changes the least throughout our life. The spiritual self can be defined by our “moral sensibility and consciousness” (James 124), it is our “indomitable will” (James 124) that lays the foundation for our actions in society. “These psychic dispositions are the most enduring and intimate part of the self” (James 124), and take a lot to be changed. We cherish our spiritual self, as it is the most personal and powerful part of the self, and most of the time can not be shared with others. 
	Last is the pure ego, which can be defined as “a wholly subjective phenomenon” (James 125). The pure ego is the broadest out of the constituents, and ultimately determines our thoughts. The pure ego is said to exist prior to experience, and is unchanged by it as well. The pure ego plays a large part in our interactions and basically determines personality. “Each thought, out of a multitude of other thoughts of which [one] may think, is able to distinguish those which belong to [one's] own ego from those which do not” (James 125). The pure ego is the most stable among the constituents, and is untouchable due to how deeply rooted it is in one’s consciousness. 
These constituents play huge roles in determining our personality. By understanding the emotions and actions they cause, the self can be defined. Along with defining someone’s self with these aspects, we can also understand how outside factors, such as other people's actions, impact the Self. 
	Most of these aspects of the Self are influenced by interactions with others, therefore, prior to the modern society we live in, these aspects of the Self could not be easily changed. The only forms of interaction could happen in person, compared to today where there are dozens of different ways to communicate. Whether it’s through a text, a call, a snapchat, a facetime, and so on, interaction has completely changed. This is taking the largest toll on the younger generations, such as my sister, who are introduced to this new modern interaction at such a young age. More specifically, the access to social media greatly impacts the development of the Self.
	The development of personality and the Self happen slowly throughout a person’s life. The most influential time of development is during youth, when the brain is not yet fully developed. The Self is developed through experience, as one can immediately realize they’re feelings and reactions to certain events, and take in those memories to slowly develop aspects of the Self and personality. Social media has unhealthily sped up this process in younger generations by exposing them to mature concepts at such a young age. 
	At the age of 11, Heidi became exposed to such content. She had multiple social media apps that showed her broad concepts such as what adults wear and say, to more controversial concepts such as political news to different sexualities. This information was quickly taken in and took part in her development. Heidi also was exposed to negative content such as cyber bullying and content posted to make others jealous or feel a need to change. This content all came together to disturb the development of each aspect of the self. 
	Social media had the biggest impact on her social self. By having a profile on an app, you can create an instant social self. She became very stressed over this concept, and would change the photos and information on her profile constantly. She tried to seem more mature in order to seem cooler, which led to confusion between her social self and how she acts in person. This idea of social media also greatly impacted her material self. For me, the phone itself was the only part of my social self, but for Heidi the content on her phone became a part of her material self. Profiles, posts, and communications on different apps belonged to her person, and she treated these apps as if they were a part of her. She would work harder on perfecting her personality shown on her social media, rather than in person. The development of Heidi’s spiritual self was sped up by her access to social media. Morals are slowly learned by experience over time, however Heidi was exposed to a large amount of content that basically determined her morals instantly. She would watch YouTube or TikTok videos that displayed strong moral decisions, and from these videos she quickly developed the sense of her spiritual self. Her pure ego was also impacted this way, as she was exposed to so much varying content in such a short amount of time. Her brain was constantly being overloaded with thoughts and impacted the development of the most important aspect of her Self.
	All of the content Heidi was exposed to impacted each constituent of the Self, which in turn increased the emotions and reactions to those constituents. This overload of emotion put great strain on the development of Heidi’s self, as well as her mental health. Being able to access such a large magnitude of mature content puts great strain on the development of the Self, especially when the ones viewing this content is a young person. Social media had forced Heidi, and multiple other younger people, to mature quicker and develop the Self faster. This exposure will continue to mature the younger generations faster, and will impair the development of the Self.

Privilege and Prejudice
There is a vast distinction between the skin colors of white and Black. One is considered privileged, the other prejudiced; and for those who consider themselves civil activists and politically inclined, then it is relatively easy to ponder a guess at which race is considered which. However, the differences between the races of white and Black for some people is much less obvious. Some may not see any difference at all, other than the obvious contrast in skin color. Others could believe the groups should be switched, and that white people are prejudiced, and Black people are privileged. A third group may think that both words are relevant and just for both races. But a privilege and a prejudice only exist because of the other. More or less, the two are codependent on each other, and they both stem from centuries of white privilege that spans throughout history and is far-reaching, all over the world. 
The argument of this reflection is not to change the opinions of those who do not see their ignorance, but rather to change their ignorance into something that fuels a yearning for them, as humans, to be better. The color of skin, or rather a difference in the majority of a specific color of skin, is never celebrated for its difference, but is ridiculed, opposed, and put into a box where its beautiful and defining factor of color is drained to be replaced by a need for survival in a society that exists on that same ridicule and opposition. But for society itself to survive, its foundation of racism, hatred, and bigotry must be the first to go.
I am white, and so is my entire family. We have never felt the blunt force of racism that is so engrained into American culture today, and we probably never will. One evening, my mother and I bought groceries at Walmart, and had a few bags-worth of bananas, crackers, and some form of candy. There was a man in front of us who was also carrying his groceries out towards the exit door. Some superstores like Walmart will have an employee standing at the exit doors to check that a customer’s receipts match up with the items in their cart or hands that they have purchased. Keep in mind, my mother and I had a few bags in each of our hands, while the man had only one or two. The thing I forgot to mention was that this man was Black. As we all approached the exit door, a female Walmart employee stopped the man to check his receipt. She tediously looked over all the items, took her time scouting his bag(s), and then let him proceed through the exit. As my mother and I approached the employee, she simply smiled and said “You’re good. Have a nice night, ladies.” 
What is wrong with this picture? That is the first question that I asked myself. How is it that one customer has to be thoroughly checked to make sure that they have not stolen anything, but two people with double the bags and items do not? It is safe to say that this is a consistent pattern that most people would admit that they have noticed first hand in their life; and most of the people that admit that would be Black. The man at Walmart did absolutely nothing threatening, or moreover did nothing to make the Walmart employee believe that he was doing something illegal. So why is it that she felt the need to question that? The answer is a few things: the man’s skin color, the employee’s skin color, and my mother and I’s skin color. 
I am thankful for the political movements that are constantly occurring around the world today, specifically Black Lives Matter. If I were not exposed to this, I would not even have noticed first-hand the situation that happened at Walmart. Being white in America means that the country and its institutions are programmed to be catered to what is best for you. A white person in America is not punished, hate-crimed, or downgraded because of their skin color. They never have to feel what it feels like to be the only Black person in a room, or to have their family members brutally killed by police for seemingly being “thugs.” I acknowledge that I have never had to feel that, and that I never will. The goal is that all white people, hopefully, will one day acknowledge that too. 
The instance at Walmart, and so many other instances like it, demonstrate how white entitlement is still so mainstream in American culture. White privilege is defined as conferred dominance and unearned benefits that give white people more power and respect in society, merely because of the color of their skin. Because of white advantage and authority, white people can argue with authority without repercussions, gain more generational wealth, and be more likely to be hired (Pager Discrimination Study). The mere concept of white privilege already indicates that there are a group of people, in a given society, that are not white, and are therefore underprivileged. The privilege in “white privilege” does not refer to a higher amount of wealth or resources, it refers to the prerogative that is given when the color of one’s skin is white. White people that are in lower income households or in poverty condemn white opportunity as a falsity, when in reality the privilege is referring to the skin color and how that promotes a white person in society. 
Peggy McIntosh, activist, and author of "White Privilege: Unpacking the Invisible Knapsack,” claims in her article that all white people are racist. Speaking as a white person, it is quite common to hear that this claim is inherently “racist” towards white people. To say that all white people are racist would be racist towards white people, right? Wrong. McIntosh states that this racism towards people of color from white communities is a distinction between racism and prejudice. She offers that white people are not always intentionally racist, but that the institutions that they have grown up in, as well as white privilege, have perpetuated the underprivileged livelihood of people of color. Institutionalized racism refers to the meaning that schools, government, churches, and communities as a whole have created a system of prejudice that is outfitted towards white people, and exclusive towards people of color. 
McIntosh shows how white entitlement works by using the example of male privilege in today’s 21st century society. “It seems to me that the obliviousness of white advantage, like obliviousness about male advantage is kept strongly inculturated in the United States so as to maintain the myth of meritocracy, the myth that democratic choice is easily available for all.” (McIntosh, 36). Men are conditioned to not see where their immunity lies and how it effects all others who are not males, and therefore not included in this privilege. The same goes for white privilege and its prejudice towards communities of color like Black, Latinx, and Asian. McIntosh’s rationale for the majority of white people’s racism would be because the concept of white advantage is the explanation for why white people are only aware of its positive qualities, and not its negative. Privilege highlights that white people are the top tier of the hierarchy of society, and because they have never been below it, they will never understand what it means to be a person of color.
Another important concept to discuss is that of racism against a majority group, in this case white people. As I mentioned earlier, it is routine for white people to frequently think that they are prejudiced against, or that people of color blaming white people for society’s problems is a form of racism. The exact definition of racism is “prejudice, discrimination, or antagonism directed against someone of a different race based on the belief that one’s own race is superior.” (Lexico). To say that white people are the victim of racism is to say that Black people are treated as royalty. The fact that America was built on the slaughter of Native Americans and the slavery of Black Americans underscores that white people are the group that has always been on top, even since the founding of the New World. Racism is not qualified when concerning white lives, because white lives have never been threatened because of their skin color. The structure of racism is a system that defines skin color, so the only way white skin is considered a positive is if black skin is first considered a negative. Reverse racism, the idea that plans like affirmative action and programs for people of color were created as a form of anti-white behavior, only exists if the concept of race itself reverses. 
With white privilege comes its labels; and white people have always been seen as respectful and trustworthy individuals living their lives showing the same respect and trust to the society around them. The definition of Black people, however, is quite the opposite. “...other groups [of color] were likely being made inconfident, uncomfortable, and alienated.” (McIntosh, 34). The Black man at Walmart, like countless other Black stories, was a victim of racialization. Racialization, from Omi and Winant, is the top-down political process where a dominant group defines symbolic boundaries for subordinate groups. Because the white employee at Walmart saw that the man was Black, she characterized him as a person of dishonesty and malice. 
The meaning of skin color is constantly being communicated through the collective consciousness and is shifting over time, just as the collective consciousness shifts. After the Civil War in 1865, Black people were freed from their slavery, but they were still perceived as lowly individuals that were less than human. In fact, part of the foundation of racism was built on the fact that many white people saw Black people as a different species, such as that of a farm animal in a field. After the Civil Rights Movement in 1968, a little over 100 years later, Black people were seen more as dangerous and violent than powerless. Because civil rights groups like the Black Panthers and activists like Martin Luther King Jr. came about, there was backlash from the collective society about how safe Black people really were to be around. 
The collective consciousness refers to the set of symbolic and shared beliefs that a society holds that informs a sense of identity. In other words, the collective consciousness is made up of everyone around us and can in turn be heavily biased towards the majority of the population. When considering this, the collective consciousness in America is made up mostly of white communities, therefore the collective consciousness emphasizes white privilege. The collective consciousness of being white is a racial formation that has been agreed upon by society. To continue, the collective consciousness brings about collective representation, and collective representation in America is American ideals of freedom and unity. But this same freedom and unity are not relevant topics when it comes to race, because neither occurs. The racism that is formed by the benefits of white privilege is an understanding that Americans have adopted because it is something that has always been there and has always been communicated. The collective consciousness, by being white in total, exposes the systemic racism that no white person has ever cared to notice or condemn the actions of. Hopefully not until now.
White privilege exists. The racial formations that have been created through white privilege exist. Black oppression exists. White and Black opposition exists. As Americans, we have lived our lives by stepping on the backs of people of color because the America that we live in serves us, and us only. Maybe if the man in Walmart wasn’t black, my mother, I and the Walmart employee were not white, this would be a different story. But it is not. The argument of this reflection hoped to encourage all of us, every single one of us, to do better – for each other. It is time to no longer step on the backs of people of color, but to extend a hand out towards them, and finally break apart the institutions of racism that have fought so valiantly and unacceptably survived. This is the chance for every Black parent to not have to tell their Black child to fear the world around them, but rather to embrace it with open arms. And this is the chance for every white parent to tell their white child that the world should not hand anything to them because of their skin color, and that they should embrace that with open arms. This is our chance as Americans, as humans, and as people of privilege and prejudice – to be a society of peace and pride.
